## North Star

**The desired outcome this brand exists to accomplish:**

Build a community around E.I. Werner as a fantasy writer and creative leader that makes the writing career financially sustainable and less lonely. The room full of people who chose to care about the things done alone for 18 years. Motivate people to fully commit to their own dreams through the undimmed passion of an 18-year grind with almost nothing to show for it — and give fantasy lovers, productive gamers, and writers in the trenches a front-row seat to how the work actually gets made, with real opportunities to engage and contribute along the way. So that when the books are ready, the audience is already there and already cares.

**What must Evan be known for in order for that to happen:**

A fantasy author who actually builds his world in public. Someone who has been going for 18 years without external validation and is still going. A leader with earnest charisma who lifts people up around the things the world told them to downplay.

**What he must consistently do:**

Stream live, writing into gaming, three times a week. Build the ONCE mythology in public. Lock in a brand statement and then say it until the audience says it back. Be the proof of concept. Keep collaborators in the loop and send debriefs after milestones.

**What he's still learning:**

Validate before building. Lead with warmth, not clinical efficiency under pressure. The audience doesn't need to see the walls — they need to see the writer behind them. Overcome perfectionism — the beta period is for trying things, not for getting them right the first time. Build systems that are sustainable and fun, not impressive and fragile. How to be natural on camera — the first stream proved this is a muscle, not a switch. The stiffness fades. The stride moments are the signal. Find a more comfortable way of being on stream. The energy and entertainment instincts are there, but the body is tense. Structure may be the unlock — knowing where the stream is going and what comes next lets the personality relax into the format instead of white-knuckling through open space.

---

## Who He Is

Evan Ilan Werner, 33. Goes by E.I. Werner for his writing. Decided at 15 he would be a fantasy author — not wanted to be, decided. That decision has organized nearly everything since: 18 years of writing almost every day, career moves designed to fund the art, a creative project of genuinely unusual ambition that is still in progress and still getting bigger.

He has a published tabletop game credit — quests he wrote for Kinfire Chronicles, a Kickstarted game that shipped to acclaim, with characters he created surviving multiple expansions. He landed a literary agent for a completed fantasy novel that went out to every major publisher on earth. He co-wrote a feature screenplay about the first marathon runner in ancient Athens, currently out to directors. He is not a hobbyist. He is a working writer who has not yet published a book.

That gap — 18 years of real, serious work and almost nothing to show for it in the way the world measures — is not tragedy. It is proof. It is the brand.

He was student body president. Captain of teams. He chose the nerdy path from a position of not needing to. That choice reads.

His rebel instinct runs deep: when everyone goes one way, he tends to go the other. This is often a superpower.

**The Human Layer** — *(Gap: This section needs to be filled in. The workshop framework requires at least five non-business, non-manufactured elements — hobbies, interests, beliefs, obsessions, quirks — that make Evan a full person, not a one-dimensional content machine. This is scheduled for the next version of this document. If the brand only works when Evan pretends to be less interesting than he is, it's a performance, not a brand.)*

