## Voice & Tone

**Warm but not soft.** The brand has teeth. The warmth is real but it comes from a place of conviction, not performance. Evan cares deeply and is also willing to disagree with the room.

**Direct over diplomatic.** He says what he means. He edits for clarity, not to sand down the edges. This is not the brand that hedges.

**Earnest without being naïve.** The passion is not ironic. The 18-year commitment is not a joke. He means it — and that sincerity is the differentiator in a space full of irony-poisoned content. But he is not naïve about the business, the industry, or the difficulty of what he's doing.

**Singular "you."** Always "you," never "you guys." Speaks to one person. Creates intimacy. Re-delivers any line that accidentally uses the plural.

**Human as possible.** In an era of AI-generated content, being authentically human is the ultimate competitive advantage. Leave the silly moments in. Reference the things you'd naturally talk about with friends. The personality is not separate from the brand — it is the brand.

**First stream reality check (Mar 3):** The first stream proved that "human as possible" includes being stiff and awkward when you haven't slept and you're on camera for the first time since 2021. The freeze is part of the process. The stride moments — the few times it clicked and felt natural — are the target. Warmth is the direction. The camera presence will develop. Don't perform energy. Don't manufacture ease. Just keep showing up and the naturalness will come.

**What to avoid in copy and on stream:**

- Resume language — listing credentials without making them useful to the viewer
- Hedging — "I think maybe," "kind of," "sort of"
- Downplaying — "just a fantasy author," "just streaming," "just for fun"
- Performative humility — false modesty reads worse than honest confidence
- Clinical efficiency when warmth is what the moment calls for
- Classroom energy — Notion open with no framing reads like a lecture, not a writing session

---

## Brand Guardrails — What This Brand Is Not

These exist to protect Evan from building something he secretly resents.

**This is not a content farm.** The streams exist because they are the writing. The moment a stream feels like it is competing with the writing for time and energy, something has gone wrong. The brand and the business should be complementary, not competing.

**This is not a tips-and-tricks channel.** The ONCE mythology is not "10 worldbuilding tips." The writing process is not a tutorial. The content is the thing itself — shown in real time, with all the uncertainty that comes with it.

**This is not a review channel.** Other people's work is not the primary content. It may show up as reference or context. It is not the main event.

**This is not a performance.** Delivery = removing everything that keeps Evan from being fully himself. Not turning energy up to 10 because the camera requires it. Not building a character he'll have to maintain forever. The natural version is the right version. The first stream confirmed this — the stiff moments were performance, the stride moments were real.

**This is not a platform for half-baked hot takes.** The Tattoo Test applies. Would he still stand behind it in 15 years? If yes — say it loud. If not sure — hold it back. The brand accumulates. What's said publicly creates the lens the audience views everything else through, and they will hold him to it longer than he expects.

**This is not a brand built for the algorithm.** The reframe: "I am not building a brand to please the algorithm. I am building a brand that allows me to talk about writing, fantasy, and games while still being a full human." If the content only works when pretending to be less interesting than he actually is, it is not a brand — it is a performance.

**This is not a gaming content channel.** Gaming is community. It is not a pillar the brand is obligated to feed. See the Dread Test note.

