## Hardware & Streaming Infrastructure

*Full hardware specs, port allocation, software subscriptions, OBS scene architecture, operational procedures, and issues log live in the OIS Hardware & Software Master document (separate living document, updated Mar 3 post-first-broadcast). This section covers the principles and summary relevant to brand decisions.*

### The Resilience Principle

The brand pillar of resilience is not just a value — it's an operational standard that runs through the entire streaming setup. The stream should not be fragile. It should not depend on perfect conditions, a perfect desk, a perfect background, or a perfect internet connection. If Evan has a laptop, a webcam, a mic, and a connection with 10+ Mbps upload on ethernet, he can stream reliably. Everything else — the Key Light, the Stream Deck, the dual-WAN failover, the portable monitor — is gravy. It makes the stream better, but the stream does not break without it.

This means: no cancelled streams because the setup isn't perfect. No anxiety about streaming from a new location. No preciousness about backgrounds or lighting. The audience showed up for the writer, not the production value. The resilience principle says: open the laptop, plug in, go live.

The infrastructure below is designed to make that floor high and the ceiling flexible.

**Current deployment:** White Plains, NY. Moving to Athens, Greece ~March 11, 2026 (Flatio booking through May 15, 195 Mbps down / 19 Mbps up confirmed).

**Streaming Core:** Gigabyte AERO X16 (RTX 5070, 32GB) → OBS/NVENC encoding · Elgato Stream Deck + (scene switching) · Elgato Key Light Neo · Blue Yeti Nano (voice) · Sony WH-1000XM5 (monitoring) · KLIM Wind Cooling Pad · iPad for chat (WiFi, zero laptop ports used)

**Camera:** Elgato Facecam MK.2 (primary stream) · GoPro HERO13 Black + accessories (travel/BTS content)

**Storage:** SanDisk Extreme 2TB SSD (primary) · Samsung T9 2TB SSD (backup) · SanDisk 256GB + 64GB microSD (GoPro)

**Internet Redundancy:** GL.iNet GL-MT6000 Router (dual-WAN failover at router level) · Netgear Nighthawk M7 Pro 5G (backup WAN) · Bingfu MIMO Antenna · USB-C Ethernet Adapter. Note: Speedify is installed but functionally inactive — current topology has both WANs behind the router, so the laptop sees one LAN interface. Router handles failover directly.

**Power Backup:** Anker 737 24,000mAh (laptop + power-only devices) · TalentCell Mini UPS (router) · ELECOM NESTOUT 15,000mAh (emergency)

**Software:** OBS Studio (NVENC) · Restream Standard (simulcast — YouTube + Twitch) · ExpressVPN · DigitalOcean VPS (available for future 24/7 radio, currently on standby)

**OBS Scenes:** Outside Inn Warmup (Holdt animation + music 100% + countdown + patron roll) → Writing Stream (facecam + Notion, music 20–30%) → Gaming Stream (facecam + game, music 20–30% or off) → Cooldown (Holdt animation + music 100%). All one-button via Stream Deck.

**Uptime Target:** 99.9% — wired primary + 5G failover + battery backup on laptop and router. The floor is: laptop + webcam + mic + 10 Mbps upload on ethernet = reliable stream. The redundancy layers raise the ceiling. They don't hold up the floor.

**Day-one validation (Mar 3):** The core stack performed. 11h39m radio run without a drop. Live stream went out on YouTube and Twitch via Restream. Four issues encountered and resolved in real time (documented in Hardware & Software Master). The resilience principle held: the setup wasn't perfect, and the stream happened anyway.

