## First Stream Learnings — March 3, 2026

*This section captures everything from the first broadcast. It exists so the lessons don't get lost and so the next version of this document can track what was acted on.*

### What Happened

Broadcast Alpha. First live stream since 2021. Evan had not slept at all. Fueled by hot coffee, iced coffee, and many hot teas. He told almost nobody — just the closest people. 8 peak viewers. No overlay, no stream alerts, no polish. Just showed up.

### What Went Right

1. **The tech worked.** 11h39m Holdt radio broadcast without a single drop. Live stream went out on YouTube and Twitch. Four technical issues encountered and resolved in real time (all documented in OIS Hardware & Software Master).
2. **The 48-hour build sprint delivered.** Animation loop from 480 PNGs, countdown timer in custom font, patron roll typewriter overlay — all built and functional before the stream.
3. **He hit his stride a few times.** The moments where it clicked and felt natural are the proof of concept. Those moments will get longer and more frequent.
4. **He kept collaborators informed.** Checked in throughout the day, encouraging and transparent. Debrief planned for tonight.
5. **Luiz signed his contract.** First collaborator contract fully executed.
6. **Carson got his contract + album offer.** Business relationship formalized, album negotiation date set (Apr 4).
7. **Merch samples arrived.** Physical products in hand — desk mat and goose print. Real feedback on quality and sizing.
8. **He went for it.** No more planning. The stream happened.

### What Needs Work

1. **The freeze.** Stiff and awkward at the start. Deer-in-headlights moments. This is expected — first time on camera since 2021, zero sleep — but it's the thing to improve. The only fix is reps.
2. **Writing stream structure.** Notion open on screen with no framing felt like a classroom. Needs a clear opening, visible session goal, and moments of audience engagement. The writing must be watchable without being performed.
3. **No overlay.** Went raw on day one. Overlays, alerts, and visual identity will develop over the coming weeks as the portrait → overlay → badges pipeline completes.
4. **Merch quality issues.** Desk mat is too square — needs wider Fourthwall format. 10×10 framed print looks blown up — source resolution too low. Luiz now knows the specs. Future paintings at higher resolution.
5. **Sleep.** Can't do zero-sleep streams. The stiffness and cognitive fog compounded the camera anxiety. Sustainable cadence requires actual rest.

### Structural Decisions Made

- **Writing → Gaming per session** replaces the old 3 writing + 1 gaming weekly cadence. Writing is the main event, gaming is the exhale and debrief with community. Fits Athens timezone naturally.
- **70:07 warmup/cooldown** replaces the 24/7 radio concept. Outside Inn atmosphere bookends every stream without VPS management overhead. 24/7 radio deferred until headless OBS + deeper catalog justify it (~April+).
- **First live writing stream: 7:07 AM tomorrow (Mar 4).** CHOSEN outline. The real test of the writing stream format.

---

## Open Questions & Gaps

*These are the things this brand bible has not yet resolved. They belong here so they don't get lost and so future versions of this document can track whether they've been answered.*

### Writing Stream Structure

The first stream proved this needs work. How do you make the writing process watchable without turning it into a performance or a tutorial? What does the opening look like? How does Evan signal what the session's goal is? When does he talk to the audience vs. go heads-down? The 7:07 AM stream tomorrow is the first live test. Track what works.

### Gaming Integration Energy

Gaming is now folded into each session as the decompression half. The Dread Test concern (gaming as a standalone content commitment generating resentment) is partially addressed by this structure — gaming is present but not the primary obligation. The open question remains: does gaming WITH community after writing energize or drain? The first few sessions will answer this. If it drains, the gaming portion can shrink or become optional. If it energizes, the structure is validated.

### The Human Layer

The workshop framework requires at least five non-business, non-manufactured elements of Evan's life — hobbies, interests, beliefs, quirks, obsessions. The current brand bible has almost none. These elements are what make the 5% personal content possible, what make the brand impossible to copy, and what prevent the brand from becoming a one-dimensional content machine. This inventory is scheduled for the next version of this document.

### Painful Problem Validation

The 16 painful problems listed across three audiences are hypotheses. The first stream happened today with 8 viewers — not yet enough signal to validate. Once streams are regular and community forms, revisit these problems. Update with actual language people use. Remove any that don't resonate. Add new ones that emerge. The workshop says: if fewer than 7 are validated after real interaction begins, the builder doesn't know their audience well enough yet.

### The Unsolved Thing

Evan was asked what he's most uncertain about with this brand — the thing that keeps him up or that he hasn't figured out yet. He didn't answer. This placeholder stays until he does. Whatever it is, it belongs in the document so it can be pressure-tested.

### ONCE Release Format

The mythology is being written. The packaging (art book, serialized release, standalone publication, read-aloud, or other format) is intentionally left open until the writing is further along. Priority: writing purity first, packaging decisions later.

### Merch Resolution Standards

The 10×10 print quality issue revealed a gap: no clear resolution specs were communicated to Luiz upfront. This needs to be formalized — minimum DPI, pixel dimensions per product size, color profile requirements — so every future commission produces print-ready art on the first pass. Same applies to Marwan for any merch-destined pixel art.

